t Michael and St George]]]]\nThe '''New Year Honours 1998''' for the [[United Kingdom]],<ref>United Kingdom list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=54993 |pages=1\u201328 |supp=1}}</ref> [[Barbados]],<ref>Barbados list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=54994 |pages=29\u201330 |supp=2 |nolink=yes}}</ref> [[Grenada]],<ref>Grenada list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=54995 |pages=31\u201332 |supp=3 |nolink=yes}}</ref> [[Papua New Guinea]],<ref>Papua New Guinea list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=54996 |pages=33\u201336 |supp=4 |nolink=yes}}</ref> the [[Solomon Islands]],<ref>Solomon Islands list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=54997 |pages=37\u201338 |supp=5 |nolink=yes}}</ref> [[Tuvalu]],<ref>Tuvalu list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=54998 |pages=39\u201340 |supp=6 |nolink=yes}}</ref> [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]],<ref>St Vincent & the Grenadines list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=54999 |pages=41\u201342 |supp=7 |nolink=yes}}</ref> [[Belize]],<ref>Belize list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=55000 |pages=43\u201344 |supp=8 |nolink=yes}}</ref> [[Antigua and Barbuda]],<ref>Antigua & Barbuda list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=55001 |pages=45\u201346 |supp=9 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and [[Saint Christopher and Nevis]]<ref>Saint Kitts & Nevis list: {{London Gazette |date=30 December 1997 |issue=55002 |pages=47\u201348 |supp=10 |nolink=yes}}</ref> were announced on 30 December 1997, to celebrate the year passed and mark the beginning of 1998. The New Year Honours for [[New Zealand]] were announced on 31 December 1997.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/node/395 | title=New Year Honours List 1998 |date=31 December 1997 |website=[[Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet (New Zealand)|Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet]] |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Honours list'' is a list of people who have been awarded one of the various [[orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom]]. Honours are split into classes (\"orders\") and are graded to distinguish different degrees of achievement or service, most medals are not graded. The awards are presented to the recipient in one of several [[investiture]] ceremonies at [[Buckingham Palace]] throughout the year by the Sovereign or her designated representative. [[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]] and [[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]] have deputised for [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]].\n\nIn the United Kingdom, the orders, medals and decorations are awarded by various [[honours committee]]s which meet to discuss candidates identified by public or private bodies, by government departments or who are nominated by members of the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.direct.gov.uk/en/Governmentcitizensandrights/UKgovernment/Honoursawardsandmedals/DG_176328 |title=Honours committees |website=United Kingdom Government |accessdate=9 September 2010}}</ref> Depending on their roles, those people selected by committee are submitted either to the [[Prime Minister]], [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]], or [[Secretary of State for Defence]] for their approval before being sent to the Sovereign for final approval. As the \"[[fount of honour]]\" the [[monarch]] remains the final arbiter for awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Honours/Developmentofthehonourssystem.aspx |title=Development of the Honours System |website=Royal Household |accessdate=9 September 2010}}</ref> In the case of certain orders such as the [[Order of the Garter]] and the [[Royal Victorian Order]] they remain at the personal discretion of the Queen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Honours/OrderoftheGarter/OrderoftheGarter.aspx |title=Order of the Garter |website=Royal Household |accessdate=9 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614210437/http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Honours/OrderoftheGarter/OrderoftheGarter.aspx |archivedate=14 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe recipients of honours are displayed here as they were styled before their new honour, and arranged by honour, with classes (Knight, Knight Grand Cross, etc.) and then divisions (Military, Civil, etc.) as appropriate.\n\n==United Kingdom==\n\n===[[Life peer|Life Peers]]===\n\n*[[Robin Butler, Baron Butler of Brockwell|Sir Frederick Edward Robin Butler]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|GCB|CVO}}, [[Cabinet Secretary (United Kingdom)|Secretary of the Cabinet]] and [[Head of the Home Civil Service]].\n*[[Ronald Dearing, Baron Dearing|Sir Ronald Ernest Dearing]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB}}, Chairman, [[Dearing Report|National Committee of Inquiry into Higher Education]].\n*[[Paul Hamlyn|Paul Bertrand Hamlyn]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}, Publisher.\n*The Right Reverend [[David Sheppard|David Stuart Sheppard]], lately [[Bishop of Liverpool]].\n\n===[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellors]]===\n*[[David Trimble|William David Trimble]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MP}}, Member of Parliament for [[Upper Bann (UK Parliament constituency)|Upper Bann]] and Leader, [[Ulster Unionist Party]].\n\n===[[Knight Bachelor|Knights Bachelor]]===\n[[File:Knights Bachelor Insignia.png|thumb|The insignia of a [[Knights Bachelor|Knight Bachelor]]]]\n\n*Professor [[John Arbuthnott (microbiologist)|John Peebles Arbuthnott]], Principal, [[University of Strathclyde]]. For services to Higher Education.\n*Peter Gilmour Noto Badge, lately Chief Metropolitan Stipendiary Magistrate.\n*Frank Barlow, {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}. For services to the Newspaper Industry.\n*[[Richard Rodney Bennett]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}, Composer. For services to Music.\n*Professor [[Michael Berridge|Michael John Berridge]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS}}, Head, Laboratory of Molecular Signalling, [[Babraham Institute]]. For services to Science.\n*Professor [[Alec Broers, Baron Broers|Alec Nigel Broers]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS}}. For services to Engineering Education.\n*George Jeffrey Bull, Chairman, [[Grand Metropolitan]] plc. For services to the Alcoholic Drinks Industry.\n*[[John Carter (insurer)|John Gordon Thomas Carter]], Chief Executive, [[Commercial Union]] Group and Chairman, [[Association of British Insurers]]. For services to the Insurance Industry.\n*Professor [[Alfred Cuschieri]], Professor of Surgery, [[University of Dundee]]. For services to Minimal Access Surgery.\n*[[Tom Finney|Thomas Finney]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}, For services to Association Football.\n*[[Terry Frost|Terence Ernest Manitou Frost]], Painter. For services to Art and to Art Education.\n*[[Michael Gambon|Michael John Gambon]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}, Actor. For services to Drama.\n*[[Geoff Hampton|Leslie Geoffrey Hampton]], Head Teacher, [[Northicote School]], Wolverhampton. For services to Education.\n*Brian Hayes, {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|QPM}}, Deputy Commissioner, [[Metropolitan Police]]. For services to the Police.\n*[[Graham Hearne|Graham James Hearne]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}, Chairman, [[Enterprise Oil]]. For services to the Oil Industry.\n*[[Elton John|Elton Hercules John]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}, Musician and Composer. For services to Music and for charitable services.\n*[[Peter North (academic)|Peter Machin North]], {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|QC}}, Principal, [[Jesus College, Oxford]]. For Public Service and services to International Law.\n*Professor John Ridley Pattison, Dean, [[University College London]] Medical School and Chair, Spongiform Encepalopathy Advisory Committee. For services to Medicine.\n*Dennis Pettit, Leader, [[Nottinghamshire County Council]]. For services to Local Government and to the community in Nottinghamshire.\n*[[Neville Simms|Neville Ian Simms]], Group Chief Executive and Deputy Chairman, [[Tarmac Group|Tarmac plc]]